<div id="review_3634624037" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3634624037" />
    <a title="Richard Swan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/122517997-richard-swan"><img alt="Richard Swan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1605093388p2/122517997.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3634624037?book_show_action=true">Nov 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Richard Swan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Richard Swan" href="/user/show/122517997-richard-swan">Richard Swan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3634624037" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1029145252366782610">In an unbroken line from The Song of Solomon to the songs of Lana Del Rey, the same imagery has been used to portray both erotic and spiritual love. San Juan de la Cruz is a, perhaps the, classic example. Do you file him under mysticism or erotica? It’s all here, the dark night (noche oscura) of the soul and the fire of love (llama de amor viva). It’s a dark paradise.</span>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

